"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, I've been working on this plan for a little bit here. Behind me is a gully. That's my backyard. That fence over there that borders my backyard. And this is a giant dead space in the middle of Houston, Texas. That gully floods periodically, and the city decided that it was cheaper to take out all the houses in this area than to fix the gully because it was overflowing during the heavy floods that we have periodically. And so all of this area that used to be houses over the past three to four years has been slowly taken out and commandeered by the Harris County flood control program and is essentially just a dead space now where you can't really develop, and we're in the middle of a residential community, so you can't, there's nothing to be done here except kind of make it a spaceway. And this is five or six acres. This is a whole block that's been taken out, and all of these houses sat on unusually large lots because of that gully cutting through the back. I want to sheet compost this thing. I want to get a massive community growing space here based on compost that I collect from throughout the neighborhood and throughout the residences and bring the community in. I want to have this space as like just an open air, open garden area. I want to cultivate a bunch of crops here. I want to cultivate flowers. I want to cultivate a bunch of stuff based on active living composting and the whole bit. I want to sheet compost across my backyard. Because I'm doing that in Needville right now, the the sh the scaling sheet composting project, but that's an hour and a half away. That's a long drive for me. And if I could do it here and interact with my neighbors and get this going in my basically my backyard, that's my goal. So I'm gonna reach out to these neighbors. I'm gonna reach out to Harris County Flood Control Program and I'm gonna see what we can do. Uh I've been dreaming about this one for a little bit, but I've been hesitant to talk about 